segments.text: June 17 or 18 on the way to Godley to do an interview checking to see if the machine is working.
OK.
This is Thursday, June 18.
And we're out in beautiful overlook with a little bit of promise of shower, chatting with Fred Palmer, class of 59.
I think I mentioned to you in advance, first question, why did you go to Texas A&M?
Why did you go to college?
How did you go?
So forth.
Well, I was like most or many in my generation.
I was the first person in the family, the extended family, that went to college.
And so I was very blessed in that regard.
My mother was the advocate for that.
My daddy was not anti-college.
He thought it was a good idea, but he was not the advocate of it.
like my mama was.
And I remember when I was just a little kid, I was watching when television was very early, and most of it was snow and a rolling screen.
I was looking at a travel program, something like the Galapagos Islands or somewhere like that.
And I was raised in a thousand-acre state park, so the out-of-the-way places and that sort of thing appealed to me.
I said, I'd love to do that someday.
She said, if you get you a good education, there's no reason you can't do things like that.
That's one of the earliest comments I ever remember about my aspiration to go to college.
I had an uncle that went to Texas, an uncle that lived with us much of the time, so he was more like a brother.
He was, you know, 20 years older, but he was like a brother.
I adored him.
He went to Texas, and you'd think that he would have had more influence on my decision to go to college.
But when I was a boy, probably 12 or something,
There were some fisheries biologists that came to Tyler State Park to do some fish management.
My daddy became fast friends with a biologist named Cecil Reed.
And Cecil was one of the earlier graduates of A&M with a master's degree.
And Cecil Reed had with him an assistant, a young man working for the summer.
And his name was Norfleet Bone, Jr. And his daddy was with the Texas Parks Board.
And those guys were Aggies.
Between Mr. Reed and Mr.
Bone, they talked about A&M.
And from that point on, I never remember really giving a lot of ball to go anyplace else with A&M.
And I thought about it mainly because, maybe because I had an interest in doing wildlife work or fisheries or something like that.
Again, raising a thousand acre state park out like that.
I'd fish before I'd go to school in the morning, things like that sometimes.
So my interest was very early in A&M.
And it might have been directed more toward the studies, but I think I remember clearly the fervor that those guys had.
And they talked about A&M all the time or A&M caps and that sort of thing.
For some reason, that influence was indelible on me, relative even to my hunger.
He was a student.
I visited with him.
I went down and spent a few days with him one time in his apartment there in Texas.
But for some reason, that never had a good, as they said, he didn't get a good scald on me.
But those Aggies had a real interesting impact on my life.
So when I got to high school, my interest was in studying wildlife work of some kind.
And it just followed that I would do that.
Now, I was prepared to go to A&M while my friends were going to Air Force ROTC and everything.
My family had some real severe financial reversals when I was about a junior in high school.
And it had to do with the lawsuit involving integration, a class action lawsuit.
by the NAACP against the Texas State Parks Board because blacks could not come into the state parks.
They sued them.
They closed Tyler State Park.
My dad was a caretaker there.
Instead of a manager, he became a caretaker.
And the pay was dismal.
We all had jobs doing something.
He pumped oil wells and, you know, hauled rocks and did whatever he had to do.
When I got ready to go to A&M, we sat down.
He said, I don't think you can go.
So I went to Tyler Junior College for two years, trying to transfer all the while.
In those days, when Daddy said, I don't think you can go, you didn't say, Dad, I think you're wrong.
I think I will.
That wasn't done.
It was just not discussed anymore.
He was a decision maker, and that's what was done.
As soon as I could, I transferred to A&M.
So you came as a junior.
Well, I came in the junior year.
That's what I mean.
I was short on hours to transfer.
Yeah.
I spent three years at A&M.
All right.
Now one of the things I've been asking everybody is describe when you came to enroll for the first time.
How did you get there and what did you bring with you physically?
What gear, what equipment?
That's a great question because you don't think about that very much.
I went to A&M.
My dad had a state pickup, and they stayed right there in the state parks.
They had transportation up to the store at the entrance of the park and so on.
So I was able to borrow the family car, and my best friend from home was going to A&M, too.

We had dates the evening before, took them home, went back out of our place in the Sandflat community off of Tyler, got our gear, which consisted basically probably just the basic stuff, a few things on hangers and duffel bags or something like that, or suitcases, and we took off.
We got to A&M before dawn.
We drove that night and got there before dawn.
We parked over by the old MSC, and I remember sitting out there when the sun started coming up, the water sprinklers came up.
And we sat there as the sun came up.
The sprinters came on water in Simpson Drill Field.
And it came down to register, and we did not know straight up.
Only thing, that's the first time I'd ever seen Texas A&M.
And I had a map, I guess, because in those days when you started trying to get in, the first thing I remember was,
But you started getting a tremendous amount of literature from Lupo's and places like that, the college bookstore.
Exciting time.
I remember that so well.
And this fall of 56?
This would be the fall of 57.
57, OK. And so anyway.
All right, then you register.
Where did you?
Went to Sevesa.
Found their way.
Didn't even know where it was.
Had a map, I guess, as I recall.
We probably did.
Made it to Sevesa.
One of the most frustrating days of my entire life was registration.
I didn't know anything about it.
Been to junior college, which is easy.
Went to Sabisa Hall, and they had this huge, you know, congregation of tables all over the place with signs about what it was.
And I'm sitting there trying to work out a schedule.
No counseling at all.
Go over in the section before, and none were open.
Then I go back, and it took me probably close to half a day to register.
And I was so frustrated, I didn't know which end was up.
And what I ended up taking, and whoever knows how that worked out.
But that was really a very frustrating thing, because I didn't know where to go, didn't know what I was doing.
And it was a trial and error thing, but I put some kind of a schedule together.
Describe the campus.
What did it look like, and what was there?
Well, in my mind, it's the campus as everybody remembers it.
I'm sure, but that's of course not the case.
The water tower was there, the smokestacks were there.
It was back when the old laundry was down there by the, you know, down there by the north gate.
And the gyne hall was there.
MSC was small.
It had been built I think in 50 or something like that.
And a friendly place, I remember that.
And of course all male.
Most of the guys were in uniform and I felt like a left shoe on the right foot all the way.
I knew what I had missed.
I still know what I had missed.
That is one of the great regrets of my life.
I can't change it.
I can't fret over it, but I'm a great advocate of A&M's Corps of Cadets because they were there and they did it.
I wasn't there, but I observed it up close and I knew what I was missing at the time.
So that campus is mostly core.
The core guys have marched the chapel.
And I believe they marched the chapel in the morning, in the evening, and I don't know about the lunch.
I don't know that they would have been launched.
I think that's correct.
And where did you live?
I lived over in dorm 16, which is over the campus there.
And I can't remember, is it Gary Hall or something, Davis Gary or something?
I believe so.
That area over there, dorm 16, it runs parallel to 60 out there.
And we used to sit up there in that room and watch the cadets go out and all the Aggies do a midnight show over at the campus there.
But I lived in 16, and I think it was the rest of my time, that's the first year, the rest of my time I was over in Walton Hall, which is the old athletic dorm.
Athletes moved out and students went in there.
Describe a typical, the routine of a typical day classes, day of classes.
What time did you get up, what did you do, where, when?
Well, I don't know what the cause is, but in those days, it would be very, very, well, I don't know anybody took 13, 14 hours.
Everybody took 17, 18, 19 hours.
I was in wildlife work, a wildlife major, and so lab was just typical.
Those are lab courses.

To take an English course or something like that was almost a break because I'm not saying I excelled in those, but the point is it was a relief because I took so many lab courses that typically school was all day long, or many of the days it was.
And so that was, we got up in the morning and my men in the Corps, I tried to go to breakfast.
Mama taught me to try to go to breakfast.
In Sevesa?
In Sevesa.
And they had the Corps at one end of Sevesa and the non-regs up on the other end, not the other end, on the east end of Sevesa I believe it was.
And of course we were intermingling to a certain extent, but we were segregated for the most part.
And the waiters of course waited tables, family style.
and went to breakfast, and I think meals must have cost us right under 50 cents a piece.
We bought a meal ticket.
It wasn't a deal where you bought kind of a meal ticket and ate over at Northgate because you couldn't afford it, number one.
The second thing is we just, I'm not saying no one did it.
I didn't know anybody that did that.
So we had meal tickets for the semester, had laundry.
I think the meals were about, they averaged a little less than 50 cents a piece.
Good food, frankly.
We all brag, but that's what you're supposed to do.
I think laundry was something like $13 a semester and running for something like $12 a semester.
I went to class, went to lunch at Sabisa.
Usually have classes at 1 o'clock.
I don't remember what it's like not to have classes at 1 o'clock.
And by golly, I was in class for the most part.
Unfortunately, when I didn't have class, instead of going to my room and studying for the most part, we had intramurals and being a wildlife guy, especially in my last year,
Sometimes we'd go out to the river and go fishing or take in those wildlife courses.
I'd go up to Binoculars out over 30 and 60 intersects south of Campbell's out there.
Those are cotton fields now, but that was a freshwater marsh out there in those days.
We'd go up there to Binoculars from the Wildlife Department and watch waterfowl and stuff like that.
Did some, had some wildlife projects out around by the airport, little lakes out around the airport.
And that's what I did on my days.
In the evenings we'd go to chow.
And I'm sorry to say that we had usually a pretty big bull session in our room right after chat.
Instead of studying, everybody came to the room and shot the bull.
All right, then let's do a Saturday afternoon and evening.
What did you and your friends do?
Well, it may lead into something we need to talk about later on, but my first semester, I was dating a girl who was head majorette at Tyler High School.
And I thought, of course, she was the prettiest thing I ever met.
And wouldn't you know it, I met her this summer for good.
And we dated all the time.
I lived out at the state park 10 miles out, and the girls would come out there, and we spent a lot of time together and had a great relationship.
When I went off to A&M, she continued to date, and I was going to also, but the only difference was there were no girls at A&M.
So we had Saturday classes.
I'd get our class at noon on Saturday.
And I typically had that little maroon Aggie bag, and I'd throw some underwear and socks and a shirt or something in there and take off and hitchhike to Thailand.
I did that almost every weekend, except football weekends.
And I remember having a date, and maybe she came that one weekend or something for football.
I don't think my mom or daddy brought her down there.
And we were home at football.
You know, and then we'd go after football.
We'd hang around, shoot the breeze.
There wasn't really much to do.
We felt very, very affluent.
We would go to the Mexican restaurant, Mexican food restaurant, over where Hilton is now, back this side, back the college side of Hilton.
Mexican restaurant out there, back in the trees, no paved roads or anything.
We'd go out there.
Or go down to the Triangle, which is where Tom's Barbecue, I think, is, right in through there.
Or go down to the Texan.
The Texan wasn't a high dollar place.
Now, those had car hops in those days.
And we'd go down there.

Occasionally we'd go down to Humdinger, which is a little, looks like a little sheet metal building down in that area somewhere, before you got to that area, right before you got to the Triangle or something, maybe just past it.
And we'd drink beer, and I think at night it cost 20 cents a bottle or something like that.
And we didn't drink a lot of beer.
We'd go down and have a beer or two, you know, something.
Couldn't afford it to begin with.
I was on borrowed money, but basically the whole time.
Youngbloods was there.
Occasionally go to Youngbloods.
Martin's, the barbecue place over there, was there.
And Steve, Bohemian fella, had that thing.
It would go down there and make a beer or something.
But that's kind of exaggerating our life.
We did that.
That's what we did when we did anything.
Go to Guy and to the movies, you know.
And I think in the spring, the Grove was open.
I think it was.
I've been to the Grove to movies before, but also went on summer tour.
Did
Did anybody ever go to Whiskey Bridge?
Whiskey Bridge.
I never did go to Whiskey Bridge because I didn't drink whiskey.
But occasionally guys would start playing cards on Saturday afternoon late and end up somewhere at Whiskey Bridge.
I was well aware of it, and I knew where it was, but I didn't personally go to Whiskey Bridge.
Correct me if I'm wrong.
Whiskey was legal to purchase in Burleson County.
That's right, right across the province.
Did, normally, did they drink it over there or bring it back this side of the river?
Oh, I doubt they drank it over there.
I think they brought it back.
In the rooms, there weren't room searches or anything.
I mean, that really, in retrospect, it was a pretty clean-cut bunch of kids.
They did some drinking, but it was not a, and loud, but in other water fights,
and jacking around with somebody in the dorm.
It was just mischievous stuff, but there was a pretty doggone clean-cut bunch of guys.
Let's see.
Let's talk about dorm or campus good bull pranks, jokes.
Describe as many of those as you can think of.
Well, of course, the most common thing that was widespread was water fights.
And to use the vernacular those days, the crapper heads were on those commodes.
And, you know, you go through the showers, and if you flushed the commodes at one time or the urinals at one time, they used the cold water so it got real hot in the showers.
You're supposed to holler crapper when you flush.
That way the guy can step out of the shower and let the time of the cold water come back and not scald him when he's in there.
There was always a guy or two around that was kind of a nerd or a jerk or something, you know, like that.
So it was always kind of fun to run down there.
when they were in the shower.
Sneak in there and flush all of those at one time.
Get to hot water, hot all of a sudden on these guys.
And of course they'd run out and you'd leave.
That was kind of good for them.
Water fights were a big thing.
Dorm, between dorms, and they'd get wastebasket, turn the showers on.
The showers were, there were showers that had shower heads on each side of the little room.
You'd walk through there down one side, back out the other, and probably most of us didn't have on a stitch.
Maybe bathing suits, maybe our clothes, and go through there, fill those wastebasket baskets up, run out of the dorm, have huge water fights out there.
It normally would start with somebody studying their room in the springtime, and somebody having a wastebasket full of water, and going to throw water from the school.
